Season 11 National Finals: Stage 1 (2019)

As we get closer to my Season 15 debut on American Ninja Warrior, I’m reminded of some of the impactful runs that led up to this moment.  This Stage 1 run was probably the biggest moment for me as I had previously failed this course 5 times in a row. Getting to the National Finals is hard enough but this one set the stage for my best season ever! 

It just goes to show that things may not always work out on our time, but keep pushing forward, and in time, things will work out. I’ll be returning to the course this Monday July 17th 8/7c on NBC.

Overcoming the Impossible

Impossible is something that appears exceedingly difficult. Overcome is to succeed in conquering it. In life, we encounter various obstacles and challenges, some of which may seem insurmountable. That's why we're thrilled to introduce Ninja Project. It's more than just a Ninja gym or a party center for us; it's personal. This journey has been seven years in the making, stemming from a desire to make a meaningful impact.

Created by Karsten Williams, alongside fellow coaches Jonathan “JB” Bange and Jacob Cantrell, we embarked on a mission to create something truly unique and special to serve the Dallas community at the highest level. Our story is filled with testimonies of resilience and determination, and we invite you to be a part of it as we continue to write its chapters together.

Over the next few days and weeks, we will be sharing exciting content and updates, as well as opportunities for you to partner with us. So, stay tuned! In the meantime, we look forward to engaging with you in the comment sections and DMs as we make progress.

In our next post, dropping tomorrow, we'll delve into the inspiration behind our logo and introduce you to the artist who brought it to life!

USA Ninja Association 
@usaninjas 

I recently had the opportunity to be a Technical Official at the Ninja World Cup event held at the Obstacle Expo in Orlando this year. This is essentially a course official that ensures a fair and safe competition for all athletes. It was an awesome experience as I got to witness some amazing performances running right next to the athletes. Leading up to the event I was invited to get more involved in the organization, USANA: The National Governing for Ninja Sport, who was facilitating the event. I was very impressed by their professionalism, organization, and ability to execute such a big event with less than 6 months to prepare. After the event, I realized there was a need to further the effort to support the growth of Ninja as a sport and continue to work with USANA where needed. I’ll elaborate more about how USANA came about but what I’ll share with you now is that this is an awesome team of parents, athletes, event organizers, and others who share a love for this sport, and want to see it grow and have success. 

I have recently committed to help lead the Media and Athlete Committee, along with wherever I can serve to make a positive and productive impact. I’ve competed on American Ninja Warrior for 10 years, coached hundreds of athletes, and hosted over a hundred competitions with my amazing team of coaches. I’ve also been an advocate for athletes, coaches, leagues, and Ninja facilities in general to help create more opportunity for continued growth and prosperity. With recent announcements of obstacle racing being integrated in the Modern Pentathlon for the 2028 Olympic Games in LA, there is a lot of excitement and questions around what this means for the sport of Ninja, and I look forward to being a voice for the Ninja community and supporting efforts that will help this sport continue to grow and be successful. Onward and upward.

Tru Momentum Elite Athlete Spotlight
Aidan Collins: @amazingninjaaidan 

Our @truninjacoaching team has been very fortunate to coach and develop so many amazing athletes over the years and we felt it’s the perfect time to highlight our Tru Momentum Elite crew! This team has earned every bit of their success and they continue to put in the work while overcoming obstacles off the course. Today, we are putting the spotlight on our guy Aidan Collins! Simply put, this kid is a beast! He’s 11 years old and we’ve been training with him for over 5 years so he’s been throwing down for a little bit. He’s won more medals and titles than all of us coaches combined and it feels like he’s just getting started. 

This kid has had an amazing year, which started with a broken foot, but finished with 1st and 2nd place finishes in some of the most challenging National Championships you’ve ever seen. We asked Aidan a few questions right before his trip to Brooklyn for the @worldninjaleague Premier Series Finals hosted at @ferox.athletics. He ended up winning the Championship 🥇 and is already back to training! We are all super proud of you Aidan!

IT’S HAPPENING!!!

After over a year of work on this project, we can finally announce THE GRAND OPENING of Neighborhood Ninjas first NINJAFIT Playground in Wilmington DE! 

This isn’t just a bunch of random ninja equipment - it’s a strategically crafted course thanks to our amazing design team (@jessiegraffpwr @teamkarsten @matt_bradley_ninja @mynameiscara @caseyrothschild @silent_kninja @the_commentator_ninja @iamalexkatz @whitmiller1 @themoustache_ninja )

This isn’t just a playground - it’s a FREE and accessible space that will help bridge communities, improve health and wellness, and increase access to our sport. 

We are creating a platform for us to continue helping youth, teens and adults to build growth mindset, resilience, community, connection, social emotional skills and physical strength through our free classes, workshops, community days and mentorship opportunities. 

Thank you to everyone who has help make this possible so far! 

We’re expecting a big turnout at the grand opening from local wilmington folks, media outlets and more. 

We can’t wait to show them what the ninja community is all about - please mark your calendars and come out if you’re able!! 

Comment “i’ll be there” below if you’re planning to come!
